   "source": [
    "# Pupil Metrics Analysis\n",
    "\n",
    "This notebook demonstrates computing various pupil response metrics:\n",
    "- PLR (Pupillary Light Reflex) metrics\n",
    "- PIPR (Post-Illumination Pupil Response) metrics\n",
    "- Baseline measurements\n",
    "- Peak constriction analysis"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d5005fcb",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## How to use this notebook\n",
    "\n",
    "Run the notebook top-to-bottom. The examples use `pypipr`'s simulated data and helper functions to compute common pupil metrics. Replace the simulated `PupilMeasurement` with your own recordings to apply the same analysis to real data.\n",
    "\n",
    "+Note: many metric functions expect a light-stimulus to be set on the `PupilMeasurement` object so post-stimulus windows (e.g., 2s, 6s) are measured relative to stimulus onset."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "id": "1923b718",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Import necessary libraries\n",
    "from matplotlib import pyplot as plt\n",
    "import pypipr"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "70ba01e8",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Quick note\n",
    "\n",
    "The examples below compute peak constriction, time-to-peak, PIPR and average pupil sizes at fixed windows. Metric functions expect a `PupilMeasurement` with a light-stimulus set so post-stimulus windows are measured relative to stimulus onset."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "id": "34a25b26",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Placeholder cell â€” proceed to the examples below"
   ]
  },

   "id": "37bd4843",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Peak constriction and time-to-peak\n",
    "\n",
    "This example computes the maximum constriction (peak change) and the time to reach it after stimulus onset. The point is overlaid on the trace for visual confirmation."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "id": "2a868002",
   "metadata": {},

    {
     "name": "stderr",

      "  warnings.warn(\n",
      "C:\\Users\\20182727\\OneDrive - TU Eindhoven\\Documents\\Tools\\pypipr_package\\pypipr\\analysis\\pupil_metrics.py:194: UserWarning: This does not correctly account for the pupil escape.\n",
      "  warnings.warn(\"This does not correctly account for the pupil escape.\")\n"
     ]
    },
    {

      "Peak Constriction: 4.01 mm\n",
      "Time to reach peak constriction: 0.93 s\n",

     ]
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",

   ],
   "source": [
    "# Load sample data\n",
    "pm = pypipr.load_simulated_pupil()\n",
    "# Basic metrics computation\n",
    "peak_constriction = pm.peak_constriction()\n",
    "time_to_peak = pm.time_to_peak()\n",
    "time_of_peak = time_to_peak + pm.get_light_stimulus().get_time()[0]\n",
    "print(f\"Peak Constriction: {peak_constriction:.2f} mm\")\n",
    "print(f'Time to reach peak constriction: {time_to_peak:.2f} s')\n",
    "print(f'Time of peak constriction: {time_of_peak:.2f} s')\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(8, 2), sharex=True)\n",
    "pm.plot(ax=ax, label='Pupil Size', color='blue')\n",
    "pm.plot_light_stimulus(ax=ax, color='yellow', alpha=0.3)\n",
    "ax.scatter(time_of_peak, peak_constriction, color=\"red\", label=\"Peak Constriction\", s=30)\n",
    "ax.legend()\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.show()\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },

    "\n",
    "PIPR metrics measure pupil size at specific times after the stimulus (for example, 6s-PIPR). This section shows how to compute the average size at a time window and the predefined 6s PIPR."

  },

   "source": [
    "# Load sample data\n",
    "pm = pypipr.load_simulated_pupil()\n",
    "# Average size\n",
    "# The average size can be determined from the pupil size data.\n",
    "average_size_6s = pm.get_average_size(start_time=5.5, end_time=6.5)\n",

    "## Shifted-stimulus example and multiple PIPR windows\n",
    "\n",
    "This example shifts the time base and sets a stimulus so we can compute PIPR values at different post-stimulus windows (2s, 6s, 8s). It also shows how the averages change when the stimulus timing is altered."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "id": "a70aedda",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "PIPR at 2 seconds post-stimulus: 5.26 mm\n",
      "PIPR at 6 seconds post-stimulus: 6.57 mm\n",
      "PIPR at 8 seconds post-stimulus: 6.99 mm\n",
      "Average pupil size at 2 seconds: 4.14 mm\n",
      "Average pupil size at 6 seconds: 6.11 mm\n",
      "Average pupil size at 8 seconds: 6.57 mm\n"
     ]
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "<matplotlib.legend.Legend at 0x2a2ed6e3d90>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 5,
     "metadata": {},

    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [

     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"

   ],
   "source": [
    "# Let's create a pupil measurement where the light stimulus is from 1 to 2 seconds.\n",
    "pm = pypipr.load_simulated_pupil()\n",
    "pm.set_time_offset(2.0)  # Shift time so stimulus starts at 1s\n",
    "pm.set_light_stimulus(1.0, 2.0)\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# The PIPR calculations remain the same, it takes the stimulus into account. \n",
    "# Now let's calculate the PIPR at 2, 6, and 8 seconds post-stimulus.\n",
    "\n",
    "# There is a short hand for the 6s pipr.\n",
    "pipr_6s = pm.pipr_6s()\n",
    "# Other times need to be manually defined.\n",
    "pipr_2s = pm.pipr_xs(start=1.5, end=2.5)\n",
    "pipr_8s = pm.pipr_xs(start=7.5, end=8.5)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"PIPR at 2 seconds post-stimulus: {pipr_2s:.2f} mm\")\n",
    "print(f\"PIPR at 6 seconds post-stimulus: {pipr_6s:.2f} mm\")\n",
    "print(f\"PIPR at 8 seconds post-stimulus: {pipr_8s:.2f} mm\")\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# The average is different now that the stimulus timing has changed.\n",
    "average_2s = pm.get_average_size(start_time=1.5, end_time=2.5)\n",
    "average_6s = pm.get_average_size(start_time=5.5, end_time=6.5)\n",
    "average_8s = pm.get_average_size(start_time=7.5, end_time=8.5)\n",
    "print(f\"Average pupil size at 2 seconds: {average_2s:.2f} mm\")\n",
    "print(f\"Average pupil size at 6 seconds: {average_6s:.2f} mm\")\n",
    "print(f\"Average pupil size at 8 seconds: {average_8s:.2f} mm\")\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(2, 1, figsize=(10, 2), sharex=True)\n",
    "pm.plot(ax=ax[0], label=\"_\", color=\"blue\")\n",
    "pm.plot(ax=ax[1], label=\"_\", color=\"blue\")\n",
    "pm.plot_light_stimulus(ax=ax[0], color=\"yellow\", alpha=0.3, label='_')\n",
    "pm.plot_light_stimulus(ax=ax[1], color=\"yellow\", alpha=0.3, label='_')\n",
    "\n",
    "ax[0].scatter(2, average_2s, color=\"orange\", label=f\"Average at 2s: {average_2s:.2f} mm\", s=30)\n",
    "ax[0].scatter(6, average_6s, color=\"brown\", label=f\"Average at 6s: {average_6s:.2f} mm\", s=30)\n",
    "ax[0].scatter(8, average_8s, color=\"cyan\", label=f\"Average at 8s: {average_8s:.2f} mm\", s=30)\n",
    "\n",
    "ax[1].scatter(4, pipr_2s, color=\"green\", label=f\"2s PIPR: {pipr_2s:.2f} mm\", s=30)\n",
    "ax[1].scatter(8, pipr_6s, color=\"red\", label=f\"6s PIPR: {pipr_6s:.2f} mm\", s=30)\n",
    "ax[1].scatter(10, pipr_8s, color=\"purple\", label=f\"8s PIPR: {pipr_8s:.2f} mm\", s=30)\n",
    "\n",
    "ax[0].legend()\n",
    "ax[1].legend()\n"
   ]
